`||p_i-sum_a lambda_a(p_i)r^a||_1<=gamma`, then the same concentration argument
gives a stochastic idempotent within `C(sqrt(delta)+gamma)`. Thus this route to
the full classical theorem is reduced to proving `gamma=O(sqrt(delta))`
approximate simplexity for arbitrary non-simplex row polytopes, or finding a
counterexample to that lemma.

Fermat sidecar probed the non-simplex case and found no counterexample. The
useful obstruction it identified is precise: one-face exposed leakage is
dimension-free, but turning several facet slacks into a global near-vertex set
can lose either a factor equal to the number of facets or an inverse
angle/altitude. Macroscopic affine dependencies such as parallelogram
relations also cannot be rounded by giving every vertex a disjoint recurrent
class. The missing lemma should therefore be phrased as an angle-free
approximate-simplexity/cancellation statement: any macroscopic non-simplex
affine dependence must either cost more than `O(delta)` negative mass or be
mergeable at `O(sqrt(delta))` scale. See
`agent-B/notes/subagent-non-simplex-classical-probe-v0.1.md`.

New correction from Popper, now generalized: bounded-coordinate non-simplex
dependencies are strongly constrained. See
`agent-B/notes/parallelogram-classical-stability.md`.

The bounded binary-coordinate cancellation lemma says: if selected rows `r_a`
have distinct binary code words witnessed by affine functions
`s_1,...,s_m:K->[0,1]`, then each `r_a` is `O(m sqrt(delta))`-close to a
probability measure supported on its own disjoint code cell. Consequently, for
all coefficients `c_a`,

```text
||sum_a c_a r_a||_1 >= (1-C m sqrt(delta)) sum_a |c_a|.
```

Thus exact affine dependencies with bounded coordinate witnesses are
impossible when `m sqrt(delta)` is small. In particular, an exact
parallelogram row polytope, whose vertices satisfy
`r_{00}+r_{11}=r_{10}+r_{01}`, cannot occur for sufficiently small `delta`.
The same argument rules out fixed-complexity non-simplex product-of-simplexes
vertex geometries whenever their factor coordinates are affine maps
`K->[0,1]`: the product coordinates supply bounded binary witnesses, while
two nontrivial factors supply a rectangle affine relation.
The unresolved issue is dimension-free treatment of arbitrary non-simplex
dependencies when no bounded coordinate witnesses are available or many
facets/factors make the `m`-dependence unacceptable.

Latest refinement: the approximate-simplexity reduction is robust to small
signed coordinate errors. In
`agent-B/notes/robust-approximate-simplexity-reduction.md`, I prove that it is
enough for the affine coordinate vectors to have coefficient negative mass
`O(delta)` and reconstruction error `O(sqrt(delta))`; exact pointwise
nonnegativity is not needed.

Wegener sidecar then sharpened the remaining non-simplex target; see
`agent-B/notes/subagent-exposed-redundant-classical-v0.1.md`. Well-exposed
separated vertices satisfy an intrinsic circuit-cancellation estimate:

```text
||sum_a c_a v_a||_1 >= (1-C sqrt(delta)) sum_a |c_a|.
```

I extracted the proof as a theorem-level note:
`agent-B/notes/exposed-circuit-cancellation.md`. In its quantitative form, if
the exposing gap is `kappa`, the error term is
`C(delta/kappa+delta)`, so the square-root bound follows at
`kappa >= c sqrt(delta)`.

Thus well-exposed affine dependencies are impossible at small defect. The
missing geometric lemma is now an exposed-or-redundant dichotomy: every vertex
at scale `sqrt(delta)` should either be well exposed with a
`sqrt(delta)`-sized gap, or be `O(sqrt(delta))`-mergeable into the convex hull
of other/nearby rows.
I formalized this target at
`agent-B/notes/exposed-redundant-dichotomy-target.md`, including the
exposedness modulus
`e_v(rho)=sup_h min_{||x-v||_1>=rho} h(x)` and the LP-dual obstruction.

New proved subcase:
`agent-B/notes/well-exposed-classical-stability.md` shows that if all
row-polytope vertices are pairwise separated and well exposed at the
square-root scale, then exposed-circuit cancellation forces affine
independence of the vertices. The row polytope is therefore a simplex, and
`agent-B/notes/simplex-classical-stability.md` gives a stochastic idempotent
within `O(sqrt(delta))`. Thus the remaining non-simplex obstruction must come
from close/mergeable vertices or non-well-exposed vertices.

New merge-compatible theorem:
`agent-B/notes/cluster-representative-classical-stability.md` proves that
global affine simplex coordinates are not needed if rows are reconstructible
from well-exposed representatives. If representative rows have disjoint
`rho`-clusters and every outside row is `gamma`-close to a convex combination
of representatives, then there is a stochastic idempotent within
`C(rho+gamma+delta/kappa+delta)`. Hence `rho,gamma=O(sqrt(delta))` and
`kappa>=c sqrt(delta)` give the desired square-root stability without
accumulating constants over merged vertices.

New exact commutative factorization theorem:
`agent-B/theory/classical-cluster-factorization-theorem.md` packages this into
